<br>
You can replace the second monk with any class, usually an SK but any class at all will work. The important part of the method was the instant agro loss from feign death only a monk could execute. Later rogues could sub in once an hour with escape but it wasn't until PoP with Fading Memories and Boastfull Bellow that any single player could do alone what once required two people to do.<br>
<br>
Because this required two players to pull off, usually two feign death classes to prevent trains if something went wrong, it wasn't something most people saw. It was used in raids and done far from the raid force. Single mobs would appear in the raid camp and that was that. It was a very rare group that had two raid pulling trained monks who would go threw the time and trouble to single pull like this. For these reasons most people think its a new trick. Its not.<br>
<br>
Some people today say its an exploit. Is it? Well yes, kinda. I don't think the game designers programed in a split second where groups of mobs would not agro on anything unless directly attacked. Role players can argue the mobs are confused for a moment when they are attacked then their attacker drops dead/vanishes. Wouldn't you be?<br>
<br>
But I'd like to point out that variations of this have been around as long as feign death pulling (also an exploit). A <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.monkly-business.com/articles2.asp?ArticleNum=98" target="top">Monkly Buisness</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> article lists <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Bind Point Splitting</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> as an advanced pulling method. &quot;At the exact moment that a mob returns to bind point and is resetting it's aggro, it is unavailable for recieving a hate list.&quot; I read that guide or one just like it back in early <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>2001</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> when I was learning to play my first toon, a monk, so this is nothing new.<br>
<br>
