<br>
The monk way is good indoors and in close quarters, against mobs that are immune to snare and mez. It's mana intensive if you screw up, so you need to be good at it. Pull both (or all) mobs you want. You can run away and fade, and hope one hangs around longer, but there's no guarentee that will work, so it may cost you a lot of mana trying to get it right. Or, you can do it smart and watch their pathing or take note of the geometery around you. Two mobs will usually split if you drop aggro the moment their pathing changes. Try running them over something, like a tree, or a corner of a wall, or a up/down a hill. <br>
<br>
Then there's the bard way of doing things. Our method gives us a huge margin of error. It works best in open zones with lots of room, but we can split 1 mob from dozens very quickly. The trick to tag your mob and start running. Once your pack of mobs is following you, simply mez your mob, run the pack away from him, fade, and double back. Tag your mob (breaking your own mez) and pull to group. This works too with snare or any other tool to delay your mob. Simiarly, you can use mez/snare to remove any mobs from the pack you don't want. Mez them, pull pack away, and fade.<br>
<br>
Then there's higher levels of pulling like bing point nuetrality stuff and secondary aggro. Check the monk boards for that info. While I argue that bards are better pullers, monks have been discussing it for longer than we have (as they're the traditional puller). <p>Virtuoso <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=895220">Bremel</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
